An `if`-`else` statement allows you to check one condition to determine one of two possible outcomes. What if we have a situation in which we need to check more than one condition and more than two possible outcomes?  Sometimes writing separate or nested `if`-`else` statements doesnâ€™t work, or is inefficient.

This is where `else if` comes in.  An `else if` statement allows you to insert additional conditions into a standard `if`-`else` statement.  This creates a different kind of structure in which each condition is checked one after the other.  The first one that evaluates to true gets executed.  If none are true, the `else` clause at the end gets executed.   Look at the examples below to see how it works.

